{"id":"1501.02847","submitter":"Peter Wilton R","authors":"Peter R. Wilton, Shai Carmi, Asger Hobolth","title":"The SMC' is a highly accurate approximation to the ancestral\n  recombination graph","comments":"Revised manuscript","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"q-bio.PE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Two sequentially Markov coalescent models (SMC and SMC') are available as\ntractable approximations to the ancestral recombination graph (ARG). We present\na Markov process describing coalescence at two fixed points along a pair of\nsequences evolving under the SMC'. Using our Markov process, we derive a number\nof new quantities related to the pairwise SMC', thereby analytically\nquantifying for the first time the similarity between the SMC' and ARG. We use\nour process to show that the joint distribution of pairwise coalescence times\nat recombination sites under the SMC' is the same as it is marginally under the\nARG, which demonstrates that the SMC' is, in a particular well-defined,\nintuitive sense, the most appropriate first-order sequentially Markov\napproximation to the ARG. Finally, we use these results to show that population\nsize estimates under the pairwise SMC are asymptotically biased, while under\nthe pairwise SMC' they are approximately asymptotically unbiased.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 12 Jan 2015 23:09:09 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 4 Mar 2015 22:05:40 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-03-06"}
